                <head>225. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On September 26, 1965, Pravda published a report on replies from <persName
                        corresp="#p_SLB1">Shastri</persName> and Ayub to Kosygin’s September 17 good
                    offices offer. <persName corresp="#p_SLB1">Shastri</persName> expressed
                    appreciation for the offer, but replied that the meeting proposed by Kosygin
                    could only take place after the termination of military actions and the creation
                    of a calmer situation. Ayub also expressed appreciation for Kosygin’s
                    initiative, but took the position that the necessary foundation for the meeting
                    should be prepared through actions taken by the <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> Security Council. (Telegram 1032 from Moscow, September 26;
                    National Archives and Records Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss>
                    59, Central Files 1964–66, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27 INDIA–<gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">PAK</gloss>)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
